					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11990202#post-4265805</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11990202/scp-4966#post-4265805</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Thu, 30 May 2019 01:54:35 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Deadly Bread</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3988532</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Hey lad, everyone has other things going on in life. I’m just exited that you got me this crit right away.</p> <p>I’ve fixed most of the minor things, along with the Site number blackbox because I honestly don’t remember why I did that.</p> <blockquote> <p>The domestic cat bit</p> </blockquote> <p>It’s just for flavor. It could live in a regular hunanoid cell, but I enjoy the little specifics.</p> <blockquote> <p>Anal fin</p> </blockquote> <p>No. It’s just the positioning on the fish that makes it an anal fin. There’s no other term I could really find for it that sounded as clinical.</p> <blockquote> <p>I’m not a organ psychic.</p> </blockquote> <p>Just a quirk of Tubbs speech.</p> <p>I’m so happy that the multiple redesigns of this were worth it, and that you enjoyed it so much!</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11990202#post-4265784</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11990202/scp-4966#post-4265784</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Thu, 30 May 2019 01:43:48 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>TheMightyMcB</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4483018</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Yet again I bamboozled the bread with promises of crit. No matter. Crit waits for no man.</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Minor&nbsp;Gripes</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Minor&nbsp;Gripes</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <blockquote> <p>SCP-4966 is to be kept within a modified humanoid containment cell sized appropriately for a domestic cat to move freely.</p> </blockquote> <p>To be honest, I don't really think the domestic cat bit is necessary. Surely if a humanoid could live semi-comfortably, so could a house cat, no?</p> <blockquote> <p>This cell is furnished with</p> </blockquote> <p>Should be &quot;is to be furnished with&quot;.</p> <blockquote> <p>Balaenoptera musculus<sup>1</sup></p> </blockquote> <p>I personally prefer using parentheses for common names next to the scientific name, but meh maybe that's just me. This is where I pick nits, after all.</p> <blockquote> <p>The only physical traits of SCP-4966 unable to be altered are it’s existing facial features and gray coloration.</p> </blockquote> <p>Maybe should be &quot;[&#8230;] traits of SCP-4966 <strong>that are</strong> unable to be altered [&#8230;]&quot;</p> <blockquote> <p>An adult male <em>Crotalus horridus</em></p> </blockquote> <p>Oh hey one of my skips references timber rattlesnakes too! That's kinda cool!</p> <blockquote> <p>an anal fin</p> </blockquote> <p>This begs the question: Does Tubbioca have an anus? How can one have an anal fin with no anus? /s of course</p> <blockquote> <p>Alces alces Americana</p> </blockquote> <p>Why is it that random ass skips end up explaining people's usernames to me? Did it for procy twice and now for alces. Funny how that works.</p> <blockquote> <p>a raid on Site-██</p> </blockquote> <p>Bluh, nitpick but I always preferred a number over site blackbox myself.</p> <blockquote> <p>I’m not a organ psychic</p> </blockquote> <p>Not sure if this is a quirk of Tubbioca speak or if this was a typo, so I'm just gonna point it out.</p> <blockquote> <p>For its role in discovering the informants, SCP-4966 was provided a bag of Tostitos brand tortilla chips.</p> </blockquote> <p>This is fantastic. Better than even the Foundation Pat on the Back Award, I think.</p> </div> </div> </div> <p>This was just a fun and cute article, and it was great. The development of the mannerisms of the plushie combined with that interview at the end and the foiling of a dastardly CI plot made for an interesting ride from start to finish.</p> <p>Take my +1, and my apologies for not being able to crit this before posting.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
